Introduction¶

A stroke is a serious life-threatening medical condition that happens when the blood supply to part of the brain is cut off. some Symptoms of a stroke The main symptoms of stroke can be remembered with the word FAST:

Face the face may have dropped on 1 side, the person may not be able to smile, or their mouth or eye may have dropped. Arms the person with suspected stroke may not be able to lift both arms and keep them there because of weakness or numbness in 1 arm. Speech their speech may be slurred or garbled, or the person may not be able to talk at all despite appearing to be awake; they may also have problems understanding what you're saying to them.

The data consists of 5110 rows and 12 columns :¶

1-id: unique identifier

2-gender: "Male", "Female" or "Other"

3-age: age of the patient

4-hypertension: 0 if the patient doesn't have hypertension, 1 if the patient has hypertension

5-heart_disease: 0 if the patient doesn't have any heart diseases, 1 if the patient has a heart disease

6-ever_married: "No" or "Yes"

7-work_type: "children", "Govt_jov", "Never_worked", "Private" or "Self-employed"

8-Residence_type: "Rural" or "Urban"

9-avg_glucose_level: average glucose level in blood

10-bmi: body mass index

11-smoking_status: "formerly smoked", "never smoked", "smokes" or "Unknown"

12-stroke: 1 if the patient had a stroke or 0 if not

Note: "Unknown" in smoking_status means that the information is unavailable for this patient.

We found that there are 201 missing values in a column bmi ,Note that this column is of type (integer) and there are outliers, so the missing data is processed by the median ,It is noticed from the figure histgram that the curve is skewed to the right (positive skewness), and this supports our choice of the median to treat the missing data ,This is done as follows:¶

In [54]:
me=df['bmi'].median()
df['bmi'].fillna(me , inplace=True)

B-Continous Data¶

- BoxPlot¶

In [28]:
cnt = 0
max_in_row = 1
for x in cont_cols:
    data = df[x]
    plt.figure(cnt//max_in_row, figsize=(25,8))
    plt.subplot(1, max_in_row, (cnt)%max_in_row + 1)
    plt.title(x, fontsize=20)
    plt.xticks(fontsize=16)
    plt.yticks(fontsize=16)
    plt.xlabel(x, fontsize=16)
    sns.boxplot(data = data);
    sns.despine(offset=10, trim=True);
    cnt += 1
  • It is noticed from the previous figures that age follows a normal distribution and the type of its curve is a symmetric curve, and that [bmi ,Avg_glucose_level] has extreme values and its curve is positively skewed

Distribution of continuous features¶

cnt = 0

for x in cont_cols:
    data = df[x]

    plt.subplot(1, max_in_row, (cnt)%max_in_row + 1)
    plt.title(f'Distribution of {x} variable', fontsize=20)
    plt.xticks(fontsize=16)
    plt.yticks(fontsize=16)
    plt.xlabel(x, fontsize=16)
    plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize=16)
    sns.histplot(data, bins = 50, kde=50);
    cnt += 1
